We got up well before first light to make sure we were at the peak before sunrise. I decided I didn’t want to google photos of this place before we got there. It’s always nice to be surprised at the peak, especially with a view like this. It did not disappoint. Definitely worthy of any bucket list. @indtravel #tripofwonders #wonderfulindonesia #indonesia

Spending this time in Indonesia @indtravel, I’ve gained a new respect for underwater photography. Like all beautiful photos, there is much that goes on behind the scenes, but underwater is a whooole different story. From the additional photography equipment, to finding and approaching the animals, to the SCUBA gear, to planning and getting to the dive spots, it’s an orchestra that needs to go together just right. Any single note that doesn’t line up, any camera setting, a current, or just bad luck can mean a lost opportunity.

This was a school of “Sweet Lips”, a large species that stays in tight fearless schools. You can get up right close and they aren’t bothered. Stunning subjects, and some of my favorite to shoot so far.

#wonderfulindonesia #tripofwonders #indonesia

I might just be as proud a Canadian as they come. If you’ve been here, you might know what I’m talking about. From coast to coast to coast, over tundra and mountains and prairies and forests and lakes, there’s no place quite like it or the people that make it up. I’m proud to call it home and happy to find out about the #Explorer150, an insane 11000km drone flight across the country with @Duracell. They are taking video all along the way and telling stories of incredible Canadians. Check out the link in my bio and find where they are today. #canada #explorecanada #sponsor

Someone told me the important things in life should come easy. And while I can see truth in that, I think back on my life and I haven't had that experience. I don't think myself a pessimist, but like climbing a mountain, I see a steep trail before the peak. In my life, the things that matter the most have also taken the most from me. They've taken time, been heart breaking, disappointing, and demanding physically and mentally. However, they've also been the most rewarding, instilling in me glimpses of the attributes that make up the best of who I hope to be, hard work, sensitivity, dedication, love, faith, humility, understanding, charity. It's when I choose to look through that eye of faith that I'm able to see pain for what it is, nothing to fear or break us down, but our weakness becoming our strength.

Hey, I'm back! Hope you guys didn't forget about me. I know, I've been gone a long long time. You see, I love photography and I love the mountains and I love to travel, but I also love my family, I love where I live, I love my friends, and I don't always love sharing everything. I've said it before and you all know it, social media isn't real life so I've just been busy with the ups and downs of life. But I did miss you guys and want to be better at sharing the work I've been up to.

Shot this the other week hiking with my buddy into Wall Lake in BC. The wildflowers are in full bloom around here.

In 1963 a volcano 🌋 pushed a large World War 1 ship, the USAT Liberty, off the beach and into the ocean just off the coast of #Bali, #indonesia. It is now an unbelievable wreck to dive, both scuba and free dive. I could have spent a month there exploring everyday. @indtravel #wonderfulindonesia #tripofwonders

Feeling grateful for the places, people, and experiences that inspire me. It brings me back to the reasons I stopped pursuing dental school and got into photography in the first place. I had no idea where I was going or how to get there, just an overwhelming passion for creating photos and the support and encouragement of you guys here on @Instagram. Thanks to those who's work I've loved to follow for years, and for those who have appreciated mine. You guys are the best. ✌🏼

When you get close to the mountains do you get excited too? Do your eyes get wide and your heart beat faster? If you know what I’m talking about leave me a comment with emojis that describe how you feel. 🏔

When I shot this picture I was on a month long road trip up to #Alaska. I remember being on the road in my old noisy 1986 Toyota Land Cruiser HJ60 and was looking up at the foggy peaks. I had to pull over when I saw this hill with thick fog that was moving like a river through the trees. I'd never seen anything quite like it. Nature never ceases to amaze me.

Before I ever bought my first camera 4 years ago, I loved to travel and hike and camp and experience new places. I never took pictures of places like East Africa, Peru, and the Canadian Arctic. I just didn't care to. Photos aren't life. I still like to put down my camera and soak in real life. I know for many people it's the opposite, but Hawaii is one of those places that make me want to forget the camera. I do still love to get a few shots though to remember it. And to all my friends new and old on Oahu, thanks. You guys are the reason I come back. #hawaii #oahu @harimarishoes #HariMari

The Canadian north is incredible. I've been to the Yukon twice, the first in August when I shot this photo and the second in January. I also lived in Iqaluit Nunavut and can't wait to go back there. The Northwest Territories are still on my bucket list. And if anyone was wondering from my previous post, it's the NWT and Newfoundland that I haven't been to yet in Canada. So I think it's great that @Duracell is doing the #Explorer150 drone project here in Canada coast to coast in every province and territory. You can check out the "Best of" videos for each location at the link in my bio. I loved watching the videos for the Yukon, NWT and Nunavut. Take a look. #canada #canada150 #kluane #explorecanada #exploreyukon #sponsored

I pulled over when I spotted a bull moose walking through the prairies. A serene sight. You can see Old Chief up there on the horizon. Chief mountain was named from the original Blackfoot name, Ninaiistáko, meaning Great Chief. It is an important landmark for locals and a sacred place for the Blackfoot people of the area. As a kid I always loved to spot the face on the peak of the Chief laying on his back, the left side of his face visible. Tell me when you see it.
